{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e28a921-020a-46b2-99e6-a1471e3f97a4","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **User apps:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System/root apps:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n**Quick lookup:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\nLook for a file matching your process name and the crash timestamp.\n\n**Other options:**\n\n- Open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n- Run `log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 10m` for system log context\n\nThe `.ips` file contains the full native backtrace, which you can then symbolicate against your NativeAOT debug symbols.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2de5a959-7761-4035-812b-16411de03128","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app that crashed on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide the key info.","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"2C60:152429:294A4E6:2DC7823:69F94C42"},"id":"dea10c80-ca15-4bb7-8e6c-ca2d19de85ef","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:47:54.325Z","parentId":"8bdb48d6-4edf-4608-8164-ec981980a701"}
